29/05/2007
Bulgarian Defence Minister Vesselin Bliznakov reaffirmed his country's support for Albania's NATO membership, during a meeting with Albanian counterpart Fatmir Mediu in Sofia on Saturday (May 26th). Talks focused on military reform and equipment modernisation. Bliznakov said his country could provide expert assistance to Albania for upgrading its army. 
*** 
Poland will open an embassy in Podgorica next month, according to Polish President Lech Kaczynski, who met with Montenegrin counterpart Filip Vujanovic on the sidelines Saturday (May 26th) of the summit of Central and Southeast European states' presidents in Brno. Talks focused on Montenegro's goals of membership in the EU and NATO. 
*** 
Greek Prime Minister Costas Karamanlis announced on Sunday (May 27th) that his country would back Vietnam's bid for the post of a UN Security Council non-permanent member in 2008-2009, following talks with Vietnamese counterpart Nguyen Tan Dung in Hanoi. Foreign Minister Dora Bakoyannis accompanied Karamanlis on the official two-day visit to Vietnam. 
*** 
The president of the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe, Rene van der Linden, paid a two-day visit to Belgrade starting on Wednesday (May 23rd). He met with Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica and Foreign Minister Vuk Jeremic. During the talks, he said Serbia's presidency of the CoE Committee of Ministers -- which the country assumed on May 11th -- affirmed that Serbia is a democratic state, committed to EU integration. 
*** 
Sir Mark Lyall Grant, the political director of the British Foreign and Commonwealth Office, held talks in Belgrade with Serbian Foreign Minister Vuk Jeremic and Deputy Prime Minister Bozidar Djelic. Grant also visited Mitrovica, where he met with a delegation of the Serb National Council, and held talks with UNMIK and Kosovo government officials in Pristina. 
*** 
Serbian Army chief General Colonel Zdravko Ponos, on an working visit to the United States last week, said defence officials assured him that US troops in Kosovo would do everything possible to protect the Serb minority in the province. Ponos said his talks on May 22nd at the Pentagon did not touch on Kosovo's future status, but focused only on security and military issues. 
*** 
International Criminal Court (ICC) President Phillipe Kirsch paid a visit to Zagreb on May 21st and 22nd. He met with Croatian Justice Minister Ana Lovrin, President Stipe Mesic and representatives of the Supreme Court. Among other topics, Kirsch and Lovrin discussed the possibility of employing Croatian forensic experts at the UN court. 
(Various sources -- 22/05/07-29/05/07) 
